F37252%2FJoint_Statement_Fifth_Annual_IndiaUS_22_Ministerial_Dialogue%5C%22%3Eno%20mention%20of%20Pakistan%20in%20the%202023%20joint%20statement%3C%2Fa%3E.%20There%20is%20not%20even%20an%20oblique%20reference%20to%20the%20South%20Asian%20country%20through%20the%20euphemistic%20term%20%E2%80%98cross-border%E2%80%99%20terror.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%202022%2C%20the%20joint%20statement%20had%20talked%20about%20exchanging%20information%20about%20the%20%E2%80%9Ccross-border%20movement%20of%20terrorists%E2%80%9D%20in%20the%20same%20sentence%20about%20the%20need%20for%20implementing%20sanctions%20against%20terror%20groups%2C%20countering%20violent%20radicalism%20and%20use%20of%20the%20Internet%20for%20terrorist%20purposes.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cins%3EAlso%20Read%3A%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fsouth-asia%2Fpakistan-is-stuck-and-india-is-stuck-next-to-it%5C%22%3EPakistan%20Is%20Stuck%20and%20India%20Is%20Stuck%20Next%20to%20It%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fins%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20year%2C%20the%20negotiated%20joint%20statement%20stated%20that%20the%20ministers%20%E2%80%9Ccondemned%20terrorism%20and%20violent%20extremism%2C%20and%20the%20use%20of%20terrorist%20proxies%20and%20logistical%2C%20financial%20or%20military%20support%20to%20terrorist%20organisations%2C%20which%20could%20be%20used%20to%20launch%20or%20plan%20terrorist%20attacks%2C%20including%20international%20attacks%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIt%20reiterated%20the%20need%20for%20justice%20for%20the%2026%2F11%20and%20Pathankot%20terror%20attacks%2C%20as%20well%20as%20the%20need%20for%20action%20against%20UN%20proscribed%20terror%20groups%20%E2%80%9Csuch%20as%20Al-Qa%E2%80%99ida%2C%20ISIS%2F%3Cem%3EDaesh%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20Lashkar-e-Tayyiba%2C%20and%20Jaish-e-Mohammed%E2%80%9D%2C%20but%20without%20any%20explicit%20mention%20of%20Pakistan%2C%20for%20the%20first%20time%20since%20the%20start%20of%20the%20ministerial-level%20dialogue.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBangladesh%20also%20featured%20in%20the%20India-US%2